%p
  In an effort to be more "visual", and to work out an unknown that's been bothering me since the start of the project, I diagrammed the framework on a whiteboard.
%p
  Pantheon keeps the game logic and the visual representation of the game state as two separate domains. It does this because of a common design principle known as Model-View-Controller.
  I could go into detail about what MVC is, and why it's a good thing, but essentially it's a way of simplifying a problem by cutting along clear boundaries.
%p
  Traditionally, in MVC, the view is essentially a wrapper around one or more models, and it presents information about the model to the user. There are two pitfalls with MVC as it relates
  to game development. One is that it is too easy to "cheat" and mix your view in with your model. The other is that you need a controller to coordinate their interaction otherwise the relationship
  is hard to maintain. But the controller itself can be hard to maintain, and a lot of extra work for no gain in functionality.
%p
  So Pantheon does away with the controller, replacing it with a message system in which views and models both speak the same language but can't cheat by peeking at each other's information.
%p
  The problem was in how to connect this low-level philosophical toy into a rendering system in a way that made sense. I had figured out that I wanted to model the UI separately and have the
  only cross-over point be a special kind of widget called a Viewport, but then I realized that other UI components often tie into the game state. Something as simple as a score counter needs to
  have privileged knowledge of the game rules, and while that could technically be solved by hooking into the message system directly, I wanted a better solution.
%p
  After I drew up this diagram and talked it over with Josh Morgan for at least an hour, I had a Eureka moment: I've got a widget (the Viewport) that I'm saying is special because it's
  responsible for the visual representation of game objects... but can't any widget represent game data, even if it's something intangible like the player's score? Clearly, the UI can't be
  isolated from Pantheon's inner workings -- the two are just intrinsically connected.

